recordings.loc: Nahma Township (south of Ogontz Bay boat launch), Delta County, Michigan
recordings.rmk: Unmodified recording. This is the recording made immediately after XC746234. Stopped car and started recording when I heard Winter Wren singing from dense dark conifer woods. Pileated Woodpecker seen landing in area and its drumming can be heard in the background.  Damp ground with a lot of fallen trunks and branches. This recording has only six songs, but the static that was heard on the previous recording has stopped. The songs are a little different from those on XC746234 by having a final lower pitched chip note. Perhaps this bird is the one that was making the distant reply to the first bird, or possibly the mate of the first. I put both of these recordings on Xeno-canto after recording XC745999 on 8/30/22, which may have been a migratory bird, a juvenile, or the song of an adult bird in the late summer season. XC745999 was recorded farther north in Delta County near Bark River.

recordings.loc: Nahma Township (south of Ogontz Bay boat launch), Delta County, Michigan
recordings.rmk: Unmodified recording. Stopped car and started recording when I heard Winter Wren singing from dense dark conifer woods. Unseen bird, and woodpecker in background, probably Yellow-bellied Sapsucker, also unseen.  Damp ground with a lot of fallen trunks and branches. This recording has many songs with reply from a distant wren. There are short static bursts at fairly regular intervals. A second recording made immediately afterwards that has fewer songs but no static, probably from one of these birds, is XC746236.

Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. I did not see the bird, but based on where the parabola was pointed the bird seemed to be perched ~5m above the ground in an oak tree ~10m away.

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 1kHz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Red Jacket River Front Park (near  Buffalo), Erie County, New York
recordings.rmk: The location was formerly an industrial site but is now a park managed by the Erie County Parks Department. The vegetation woody vegetation is dominated by Eastern Cottonwood (Populus deltoides) and the open areas a mix of native herbaceous plants with patches of Phragmites (Phragmites australis) and Mugwort (Artemisia vulgaris). The bird was foraging on the ground and began to call when I was near. While this species does breed locally at higher elevations in the southern part of the county the Cattaraugus foothills, suitable habitat does not exist in this location. Winter Wren has been noted by other at this location, but this is the first observation for me at the park. eBird checklist here: https://ebird.org/atlasny/checklist/S106114021

recordings.loc: Four Mile Lake, Kawartha Lakes, Ontario
recordings.rmk:
New to X-C and I am trying to identify this bird. He sings often and is  just out of sight. I know approximately where he is in the trees but have not been able to see him yet. There are many trees (very tall) around as it is a somewhat wooded area on the shores of a lake. Lots of birch, maple, pine, cedar, etc. I have heard him many times over the last 5 weeks. Always close enough to hear well but never able to find him. I've only ever heard him during the daytime. Say from 8 am to 8 pm. This was recorded in early afternoon. 

The recording is not modified in any way. I started recording mid-song and then there is a lull where he is quiet (neighbour sneezes) and then he sings his full song. It was recorded on an iPhone 6S and then converted to an MP3 file. 

Any help would be appreciated.

Thank you.

recordings.loc: Alder St, Queen Charlotte, British Columbia
recordings.rmk:
Apparent Eastern Winter Wren, out of range.   Unedited audio extracted from camera video clips taken over a 30 minute period at dusk, during which the bird called only occasionally.  Only visuals on the bird were fleeting glimpses of the bird in short flights inside a salmonberry thicket - views were good enough to see the obvious shape/size of a Troglodytes wren, but too poor to see any colouration on the bird.  

This bird was also heard giving rapid trilled "ratchet" calls twice, but I did not manage to record these.  These "ratchet" calls had the same sound quality as the "chip" calls in this recording - much softer and lower-pitched than Pacific Wren ratchet calls, with a quality reminiscent of Song Sparrow calls.  The "ratchet" calls sounded like those on this recording:

http://www.xeno-canto.org/251804

Pueblo Canyon, Los Alamos, Los Alamos County, New Mexico
recordings.rmk:
This recording was made using the in-camera microphone on a Canon 7D Mk II  DSLR.  The audio was extracted from the video using Audacity, then the "Noise Removal" effect was applied globally, using a ~1s section of audio with no bird sounds as the noise profile.   The result was then amplified by 15 dB.  

The bird was seen flying among dead riparian plants along the Pueblo Canyon stream, which was frozen solid.   It had been seen earlier in the day by another local birder.  She indicated that the bird did not respond to Winter Wren calls but responded aggressively to Pacific Wren calls.   When I arrived, I did not hear the bird calling, so I played a WIWR call and got no response.  I then played the PAWR song and the bird flew right up to me and [perched for an excellent picture](https://www.flickr.com/photos/mouser-nerdbot/16464973691/).  After that, it flew away and was then heard calling regularly for at least 10 minutes.  It was during this time that I took a video with my camera to capture the call audio.  

The above photo does not show the back of the bird; [here is another photo taken in the same place the following day by another local birder](https://www.flickr.com/photos/92060064@N04/16289576820/) (this is very likely to be the same individual, as WIWR are quite rare here).
